# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pillow-imaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] In computer graphics, **alpha compositing** or **alpha blending** is the process of combining one image with a background to create the appearance of partial or full transparency.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] It is often useful to render picture elements (pixels) in separate passes or layers and then combine the resulting 2D images into a single, final image called the composite.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Compositing is used extensively in film when combining computer-rendered image elements with live footage.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Alpha blending is also used in 2D computer graphics to put rasterized foreground elements over a background.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] In order to combine the picture elements of the images correctly, it is necessary to keep an associated *matte* for each element in addition to its color.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] This matte layer contains the coverage information—the shape of the geometry being drawn—making it possible to distinguish between parts of the image where something was drawn and parts that are empty.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Although the most basic operation of combining two images is to put one over the other, there are many operations, or blend modes, that are used.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The concept of an alpha channel was introduced by Alvy Ray Smith and Ed Catmull in the late 1970s at the New York Institute of Technology Computer Graphics Lab.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Wallace derived the same straight **over** operator based on a physical reflectance/transmittance model in 1981.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] A 1984 paper by Thomas Porter and Tom Duff introduced premultiplied alpha using a geometrical approach.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The use of the term *alpha* is explained by Smith as follows: "We called it that because of the classic linear interpolation formula $\alpha A+(1-\alpha )B$ that uses the Greek letter $\alpha$ (alpha) to control the amount of interpolation between, in this case, two images A and B".
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] That is, when compositing image A atop image B, the value of $\alpha$ in the formula is taken directly from A's alpha channel.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] In a 2D image a color combination is stored for each picture element (pixel), often a combination of red, green and blue (RGB).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] When alpha compositing is in use, each pixel has an additional numeric value stored in its **alpha channel**, with a value ranging from 0 to 1.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] A value of 0 means that the pixel is fully transparent and the color in the pixel beneath will show through.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] A value of 1 means that the pixel is fully opaque.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] With the existence of an alpha channel, it is possible to express compositing image operations using a *compositing algebra*.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] For example, given two images *A* and *B*, the most common compositing operation is to combine the images so that *A* appears in the foreground and *B* appears in the background.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] This can be expressed as *A* **over** *B*.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The **over** operator is, in effect, the normal painting operation (see Painter's algorithm).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The **in** and **out** operators are the alpha compositing equivalent of clipping.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The two use only the alpha channel of the second image and ignore the color components.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] In addition, **plus** defines additive blending.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] If an alpha channel is used in an image, there are two common representations that are available: straight (unassociated) alpha and premultiplied (associated) alpha.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The most significant advantage of premultiplied alpha is that it allows for correct blending, interpolation, and filtering.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Ordinary interpolation without premultiplied alpha leads to RGB information leaking out of fully transparent (A=0) regions, even though this RGB information is ideally invisible.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] When interpolating or filtering images with abrupt borders between transparent and opaque regions, this can result in borders of colors that were not visible in the original image.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Errors also occur in areas of semitransparency because the RGB components are not correctly weighted, giving incorrectly high weighting to the color of the more transparent (lower alpha) pixels.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Premultiplied alpha may also be used to allow regions of regular alpha blending (e.g. smoke) and regions with additive blending mode (e.g. flame and glitter effects) to be encoded within the same image.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] This is represented by an RGBA triplet that express emission with no occlusion, such as (0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.0).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Another advantage of premultiplied alpha is performance; in certain situations, it can reduce the number of multiplication operations (e.g. if the image is used many times during later compositing).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The Porter–Duff operations have a simple form only in premultiplied alpha.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Some rendering pipelines expose a "straight alpha" API surface, but converts them into premultiplied alpha for performance.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] One disadvantage of premultiplied alpha is that it can reduce the available relative precision in the RGB values when using integer or fixed-point representation for the color components.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] This may cause a noticeable loss of quality if the color information is later brightened or if the alpha channel is removed.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] In practice, this is not usually noticeable because during typical composition operations, such as OVER, the influence of the low-precision color information in low-alpha areas on the final output image (after composition) is correspondingly reduced.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] This loss of precision also makes premultiplied images easier to compress using certain compression schemes, as they do not record the color variations hidden inside transparent regions, and can allocate fewer bits to encode low-alpha areas.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The same “limitations” of lower quantisation bit depths such as 8 bit per channel are also present in imagery without alpha, and this argument is problematic as a result.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Assuming that the pixel color is expressed using *straight* (non-premultiplied) RGBA tuples, a pixel value of (0, 0.7, 0, 0.5) implies a pixel that has 70% of the maximum green intensity and 50% opacity.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] If the color were fully green, its RGBA would be (0, 1, 0, 0.5).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] However, if this pixel uses premultiplied alpha, all of the RGB values (0, 0.7, 0) are multiplied, or scaled for occlusion, by the alpha value 0.5, which is appended to yield (0, 0.35, 0, 0.5).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] In this case, the 0.35 value for the G channel actually indicates 70% green emission intensity (with 50% occlusion).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] A pure green emission would be encoded as (0, 0.5, 0, 0.5).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Knowing whether a file uses straight or premultiplied alpha is essential to correctly process or composite it, as a different calculation is required.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Emission with no occlusion cannot be represented in straight alpha.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] No conversion is available in this case.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] The most popular image formats that support the alpha channel are PNG and TIFF.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] GIF supports 1-bit transparency by designating one palette entry as transparent.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Support for alpha channels is present in some video codecs, such as Animation and Apple ProRes 4444 of the QuickTime format, or in the Techsmith multi-format codec.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] This transformation better utilizes the limited number of bits in the encoded image by choosing $\gamma$ that better matches the non-linear human perception of luminance.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] When combined with premultiplied alpha, pre-multiplication is done in linear space, prior to gamma compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Note that the alpha channel may or may not undergo gamma-correction, even when the color channels do.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Although used for similar purposes, transparent colors and image masks do not permit the smooth blending of the superimposed image pixels with those of the background (only whole image pixels or whole background pixels allowed).
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] A similar effect can be achieved with a 1-bit alpha channel, as found in the 16-bit RGBA high color mode of the Truevision TGA image file format and related TARGA and AT-Vista/NU-Vista display adapters' high color graphic mode.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] This mode devotes 5 bits for every primary RGB color (15-bit RGB) plus a remaining bit as the "alpha channel".
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Dithering can be used to simulate partial occlusion where only 1-bit alpha is available.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] For some applications, a single alpha channel is not sufficient: a stained-glass window, for instance, requires a separate transparency channel for each RGB channel to model the red, green and blue transparency separately.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] More alpha channels can be added for accurate spectral color filtration applications.
[src:pillow-imaging/alpha-compositing] Some order-independent transparency methods replace the **over** operator with a commutative approximation.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A **color space** is a specific organization of colors.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] In combination with color profiling supported by various physical devices, it supports reproducible representations of color – whether such representation entails an analog or a digital representation.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A "color space" is a useful conceptual tool for understanding the color capabilities of a particular device or digital file.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] When trying to reproduce color on another device, color spaces can show whether shadow/highlight detail and color saturation can be retained, and by how much either will be compromised.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Adding a specific mapping function between a color model and a reference color space establishes within the reference color space a definite "footprint", known as a *gamut*, and for a given color model, this defines a color space.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] For example, Adobe RGB and sRGB are two different absolute color spaces, both based on the RGB color model.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] When defining a color space, the usual reference standard is the CIELAB or CIEXYZ color spaces, which were specifically designed to encompass all colors the average human can see.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Since "color space" identifies a particular combination of the color model and the mapping function, the word is often used informally to identify a color model.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] However, even though identifying a color space automatically identifies the associated color model, this usage is incorrect in a strict sense.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] For example, although several specific color spaces are based on the RGB color model, there is no such thing as the singular RGB color space.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] In 1802, Thomas Young postulated the existence of three types of photoreceptors (now known as cone cells) in the eye, each of which was sensitive to a particular range of visible light.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Hermann von Helmholtz developed the Young–Helmholtz theory further in 1850: that the three types of cone photoreceptors could be classified as short-preferring (blue), middle-preferring (green), and long-preferring (red), according to their response to the wavelengths of light striking the retina.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The relative strengths of the signals detected by the three types of cones are interpreted by the brain as a visible color.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] But it is not clear that they thought of colors as being points in color space.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The color-space concept was likely due to Hermann Grassmann, who developed it in two stages.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] First, he developed the idea of vector space, which allowed the algebraic representation of geometric concepts in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] With this conceptual background, in 1853, Grassmann published a theory of how colors mix; it and its three color laws are still taught, as Grassmann's law.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Colors can be created in printing with color spaces based on the CMYK color model, using the subtractive primary colors of pigment (**c**yan, **m**agenta, **y**ellow, and **k**ey [black]).
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] To create a three-dimensional representation of a given color space, we can assign the amount of magenta color to the representation's X axis, the amount of cyan to its Y axis, and the amount of yellow to its Z axis.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The resulting 3-D space provides a unique position for every possible color that can be created by combining those three pigments.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Colors can be created on computer monitors with color spaces based on the RGB color model, using the additive primary colors (red, green, and blue).
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A three-dimensional representation would assign each of the three colors to the X, Y, and Z axes.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Colors generated on a given monitor will be limited by the reproduction medium, such as the phosphor (in a CRT monitor) or filters and backlight (LCD monitor).
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Another way of creating colors on a monitor is with an HSL or HSV color model, based on hue, saturation, brightness (value/lightness).
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] With such a model, the variables are assigned to cylindrical coordinates.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Many color spaces can be represented as three-dimensional values in this manner, but some have more, or fewer dimensions, and some, such as Pantone, cannot be represented in this way at all.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Color space conversion is the translation of the representation of a color from one basis to another.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] This typically occurs in the context of converting an image that is represented in one color space to another color space, the goal being to make the translated image look as similar as possible to the original.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The RGB color model is implemented in different ways, depending on the capabilities of the system used.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The most common incarnation in general use as of 2021 is the 24-bit implementation, with 8 bits, or 256 discrete levels of color per channel.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Any color space based on such a 24-bit RGB model is thus limited to a range of 256×256×256 ≈ 16.7 million colors.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Some implementations use 16 bits per component for 48 bits total, resulting in the same gamut with a larger number of distinct colors.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] This is especially important when working with wide-gamut color spaces (where most of the more common colors are located relatively close together), or when a large number of digital filtering algorithms are used consecutively.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The same principle applies for any color space based on the same color model, but implemented at different bit depths.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] CIE 1931 XYZ color space was one of the first attempts to produce a color space based on measurements of human color perception (earlier efforts were by James Clerk Maxwell, König & Dieterici, and Abney at Imperial College) and it is the basis for almost all other color spaces.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The CIERGB color space is a linearly-related companion of CIE XYZ.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Additional derivatives of CIE XYZ include the CIELUV, CIEUVW, and CIELAB.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] RGB uses additive color mixing, because it describes what kind of *light* needs to be *emitted* to produce a given color.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] RGB stores individual values for red, green and blue.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] RGBA is RGB with an additional channel, alpha, to indicate transparency.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Common color spaces based on the RGB model include sRGB, Adobe RGB, ProPhoto RGB, scRGB, and CIE RGB.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] CMYK uses subtractive color mixing used in the printing process, because it describes what kind of inks need to be applied so the light *reflected* from the substrate and through the inks produces a given color.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] One starts with a white substrate (canvas, page, etc.), and uses ink to subtract color from white to create an image.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] CMYK stores ink values for cyan, magenta, yellow and black.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] There are many CMYK color spaces for different sets of inks, substrates, and press characteristics (which change the dot gain or transfer function for each ink and thus change the appearance).
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] YIQ was formerly used in NTSC (North America, Japan and elsewhere) television broadcasts for historical reasons.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] This system stores a luma value roughly analogous to (and sometimes incorrectly identified as) luminance, along with two chroma values as approximate representations of the relative amounts of blue and red in the color.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] It is similar to the YUV scheme used in most video capture systems and in PAL (Australia, Europe, except France, which uses SECAM) television, except that the YIQ color space is rotated 33° with respect to the YUV color space and the color axes are swapped.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The YDbDr scheme used by SECAM television is rotated in another way.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] It is most commonly seen in its digital form, YCbCr, used widely in video and image compression schemes such as MPEG and JPEG.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] xvYCC is an international digital video color space standard published by the IEC (IEC 61966-2-4).
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] It is based on the ITU BT.601 and BT.709 standards but extends the gamut beyond the R/G/B primaries specified in those standards.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] HSV (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **v**alue), also known as HSB (hue, saturation, **b**rightness) is often used by artists because it is often more natural to think about a color in terms of hue and saturation than in terms of additive or subtractive color components.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] HSV is a transformation of an RGB color space, and its components and colorimetry are relative to the RGB color space from which it was derived.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] HSL (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **l**ightness/**l**uminance), also known as HLS or HSI (hue, saturation, **i**ntensity) is quite similar to HSV, with "lightness" replacing "brightness".
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The difference is that the *brightness* of a pure color is equal to the brightness of white, while the *lightness* of a pure color is equal to the lightness of a medium gray.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] They largely ignored blue light because the added complexity of a 3-component process provided only a marginal increase in fidelity when compared to the jump from monochrome to 2-component color.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] In this article, we concentrate on the second definition.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] CIEXYZ, sRGB, and ICtCp are examples of absolute color spaces, as opposed to a generic RGB color space.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A non-absolute color space can be made absolute by defining its relationship to absolute colorimetric quantities.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] For instance, if the red, green, and blue colors in a monitor are measured exactly, together with other properties of the monitor, then RGB values on that monitor can be considered as absolute.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The CIE 1976 L*, a*, b* color space is sometimes referred to as absolute, though it also needs a white point specification to make it so.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A popular way to make a color space like RGB into an absolute color is to define an ICC profile, which contains the attributes of the RGB.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] This is not the only way to express an absolute color, but it is the standard in many industries.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] RGB colors defined by widely accepted profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The process of adding an ICC profile to a graphic or document is sometimes called *tagging* or *embedding*; tagging, therefore, marks the absolute meaning of colors in that graphic or document.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A color in one absolute color space can be converted into another absolute color space, and back again, in general; however, some color spaces may have gamut limitations, and converting colors that lie outside that gamut will not produce correct results.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] There are also likely to be rounding errors, especially if the popular range of only 256 distinct values per component (8-bit color) is used.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] One part of the definition of an absolute color space is the viewing conditions.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] The same color, viewed under different natural or artificial lighting conditions, will look different.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Those involved professionally with color matching may use viewing rooms, lit by standardized lighting.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Occasionally, there are precise rules for converting between non-absolute color spaces.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] For example, HSL and HSV spaces are defined as mappings of RGB.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] Both are non-absolute, but the conversion between them should maintain the same color.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] However, in general, converting between two non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to CMYK) or between absolute and non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to L*a*b*) is almost a meaningless concept.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A different method of defining absolute color spaces is familiar to many consumers as the swatch card, used to select paint, fabrics, and the like.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] This is a way of agreeing a color between two parties.
[src:pillow-imaging/color-space] A more standardized method of defining absolute colors is the Pantone Matching System, a proprietary system that includes swatch cards and recipes that commercial printers can use to make inks that are a particular color.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The purpose of early image processing was to improve the quality of the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] In image processing, the input is a low-quality image, and the output is an image with improved quality.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Common image processing includes image enhancement, restoration, encoding, and compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The first successful application was the American Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL).
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] They used image processing techniques such as geometric correction, gradation transformation, noise removal, etc. on the thousands of lunar photos sent back by the Space Detector Ranger 7 in 1964, taking into account the position of the Sun and the environment of the Moon.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The impact of the successful mapping of the Moon's surface map by the computer has been a success.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Later, more complex image processing was performed on the nearly 100,000 photos sent back by the spacecraft, so that the topographic map, color map and panoramic mosaic of the Moon were obtained, which achieved extraordinary results and laid a solid foundation for human landing on the Moon.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The cost of processing was fairly high, however, with the computing equipment of that era.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] That changed in the 1970s, when digital image processing proliferated as cheaper computers and dedicated hardware became available.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] This led to images being processed in real-time, for some dedicated problems such as television standards conversion.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] As general-purpose computers became faster, they started to take over the role of dedicated hardware for all but the most specialized and computer-intensive operations.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] With the fast computers and signal processors available in the 2000s, digital image processing has become the most common form of image processing, and is generally used because it is not only the most versatile method, but also the cheapest.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The basis for modern image sensors is metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, This led to the development of digital semiconductor image sensors, including the charge-coupled device (CCD) and later the CMOS sensor.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The charge-coupled device was invented by Willard S.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] While researching MOS technology, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The CCD is a semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The NMOS active-pixel sensor (APS) was invented by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] This was enabled by advances in MOS semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The NMOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) was later developed by Eric Fossum's team at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] By 2007, sales of CMOS sensors had surpassed CCD sensors.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] MOS image sensors are widely used in optical mouse technology.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The first optical mouse, invented by Richard F.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Lyon at Xerox in 1980, used a 5 μm NMOS integrated circuit sensor chip.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Since the first commercial optical mouse, the IntelliMouse introduced in 1999, most optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] An important development in digital image compression technology was the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a lossy compression technique first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] DCT compression became the basis for JPEG, which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group in 1992.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] JPEG compresses images down to much smaller file sizes, and has become the most widely used image file format on the Internet.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Its highly efficient DCT compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos, with several billion JPEG images produced every day as of 2015.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Medical imaging techniques produce very large amounts of data, especially from CT, MRI and PET modalities.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] As a result, storage and communications of electronic image data are prohibitive without the use of compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] JPEG 2000 image compression is used by the DICOM standard for storage and transmission of medical images.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The cost and feasibility of accessing large image data sets over low or various bandwidths are further addressed by use of another DICOM standard, called JPIP, to enable efficient streaming of the JPEG 2000 compressed image data.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Electronic signal processing was revolutionized by the wide adoption of MOS technology in the 1970s.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] MOS integrated circuit technology was the basis for the first single-chip microprocessors and microcontrollers in the early 1970s, and then the first single-chip digital signal processor (DSP) chips in the late 1970s.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] DSP chips have since been widely used in digital image processing.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) image compression algorithm has been widely implemented in DSP chips, with many companies developing DSP chips based on DCT technology.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] DCTs are widely used for encoding, decoding, video coding, audio coding, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, analog-to-digital conversion, formatting luminance and color differences, and color formats such as YUV444 and YUV411.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Digital image processing allows the use of much more complex algorithms, and hence, can offer both more sophisticated performance at simple tasks, and the implementation of methods which would be impossible by analogue means.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Digital filters are used to blur and sharpen digital images.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Notice that the highpass filter shows extra edges when zero padded compared to the repeated edge padding.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] MATLAB example for spatial domain highpass filtering.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] To apply the affine matrix to an image, the image is converted to a matrix in which each entry corresponds to the pixel intensity at that location.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Then each pixel's location can be represented as a vector indicating the coordinates of that pixel in the image, [*x*, *y*], where *x* and *y* are the row and column of a pixel in the image matrix.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate to be multiplied by an affine-transformation matrix, which gives the position that the pixel value will be copied to in the output image.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] However, to allow transformations that require translation transformations, 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates are needed.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The third dimension is usually set to a non-zero constant, usually 1, so that the new coordinate is [*x*, *y*, 1].
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate vector to be multiplied by a 3×3 matrix, enabling translation shifts.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Thus, the third dimension, i.e., the constant 1, allows translation.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Because matrix multiplication is associative, multiple affine transformations can be combined into a single affine transformation by multiplying the matrix of each individual transformation in the order that the transformations are done.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] This results in a single matrix that, when applied to a point vector, gives the same result as all the individual transformations performed on the vector [*x*, *y*, 1] in sequence.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Thus, a sequence of affine transformation matrices can be reduced to a single affine transformation matrix.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] For example, 2-dimensional coordinates only permit rotation about the origin (0, 0).
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] But 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates can be used to first translate any point to (0, 0), then perform the rotation, and lastly translate the origin (0, 0) back to the original point (the opposite of the first translation).
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] These three affine transformations can be combined into a single matrix, thus allowing rotation around any point in the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Mathematical morphology (MM) is a nonlinear image processing framework that analyzes shapes within images by probing local pixel neighborhoods using a small, predefined function called a structuring element.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] In the context of grayscale images, MM is especially useful for denoising through dilation and erosion—primitive operators that can be combined to build more complex filters.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Here, ${\mathcal {S}}$ defines the neighborhood of relative coordinates $(m,n)$ over which local operations are computed.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The values of $B(m,n)$ bias the image during dilation and erosion.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] MM operations, such as opening and closing, are composite processes that utilize both dilation and erosion to modify the structure of an image.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] These operations are particularly useful for tasks such as noise removal, shape smoothing, and object separation.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] For example, applying opening to an image f with a structuring element B would first reduce small details (through erosion) and then restore the main shapes (through dilation).
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] This ensures that unwanted noise is removed without significantly altering the size or shape of larger objects.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] For instance, applying closing to the same image f would fill in small gaps within objects, such as connecting breaks in thin lines or closing small holes, while ensuring that the surrounding areas are not significantly affected.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Both opening and closing can be visualized as ways of refining the structure of an image: opening simplifies and removes small, unnecessary details, while closing consolidates and connects objects to form more cohesive structures.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Digital cameras generally include specialized digital image processing hardware – either dedicated chips or added circuitry on other chips – to convert the raw data from their image sensor into a color-corrected image in a standard image file format.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Additional post-processing techniques increase edge sharpness or color saturation to create more naturally looking images.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Face detection can be implemented with mathematical morphology, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), and horizontal projection.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The feature-based method of face detection uses skin tone, edge detection, face shape, and features of a face (like eyes, mouth, etc.) to achieve face detection.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The skin tone, face shape, and all the unique elements that only the human face has can be described as features.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Normally, HSV or RGB color spaces are suitable for the skin filter.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] After filtering images with skin tone, to get the face edge, morphology and DCT are used to remove noise and fill up missing skin areas.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] DCT is to avoid the object with skin-like tone.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Since human faces always have higher texture.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Sobel operator or other operators can be applied to detect face edge.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] To position human features like eyes, using the projection and finding the peak of the histogram of projection helps to get the detailed features like mouth, hair, and lip.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Image quality can be influenced by camera vibration, over-exposure, gray level distribution too centralized, and noise, etc.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] For example, the noise problem can be solved by smoothing method, while the gray level distribution problem can be improved by histogram equalization.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] In drawing, if there is some dissatisfied color, taking some color around the dissatisfied color and averaging them.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The smoothing method can be implemented with a mask and convolution.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Take the small image and mask, for instance, as below.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] The original image pixel is 1, 4, 28, 30.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] After the smoothing mask, the pixel becomes 9, 10, 9, 9, respectively.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Generally, given a gray level histogram from an image as below.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Changing the histogram to a uniform distribution from an image is usually what we call histogram equalization.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] In discrete time, the area of gray level histogram is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}H(p_{i})$ (see figure 1) while the area of uniform distribution is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}G(q_{i})$ (see figure 2).
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] Moreover, based on the definition of a function, the Gray level histogram method is like finding a function f that satisfies f(p)=q.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] **Variability in image quality**: Variations in image quality and resolution, including blurry images and incomplete details, can hinder uniform processing across a database.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] **Object detection and Recognition**: Identifying and recognising objects within images, especially in complex scenarios with multiple objects and occlusions, poses a significant challenge.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] **Data annotation and labelling**: Labelling diverse and multiple images for machine recognition is crucial for further processing accuracy, as incorrect identification can lead to unrealistic results.
[src:pillow-imaging/digital-image-processing] **Computational resource intensity**: Accessing adequate computational resources for image processing can be challenging and costly, hindering progress without sufficient resources.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] An **image file format** is a file format for a digital image.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] There are many formats that can be used, such as JPEG, PNG, and GIF.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Most formats up until 2022 were for storing 2D images, not 3D ones.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The data stored in an image file format may be compressed or uncompressed.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] If the data is compressed, it may be done so using lossy compression or lossless compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] For graphic design applications, vector formats are often used.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Some image file formats support transparency.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] A 3D image can be represented within a 2D format, as in a stereogram or autostereogram, but this 3D image will not be a true light field, and thereby may cause the vergence–accommodation conflict.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Image files are composed of digital data in one of these formats so that the data can be displayed on a digital (computer) display or printed out using a printer.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] A common method for displaying digital image information has historically been rasterization.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The size of raster image files is positively correlated with the number of pixels in the image and the color depth (bits per pixel).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Images can be compressed in various ways, however.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] A compression algorithm stores either an exact representation or an approximation of the original image in a smaller number of bytes that can be expanded back to its uncompressed form with a corresponding decompression algorithm.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Images with the same number of pixels and color depth can have very different compressed file sizes.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Considering exactly the same compression, number of pixels, and color depth for two images, different graphical complexity of the original images may also result in very different file sizes after compression due to the nature of compression algorithms.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] With some compression formats, images that are less complex may result in smaller compressed file sizes.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] This characteristic sometimes results in a smaller file size for some lossless formats than lossy formats.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] For example, graphically simple images (i.e., images with large continuous regions like line art or animation sequences) may be losslessly compressed into a GIF or PNG format and result in a smaller file size than a lossy JPEG format.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] With vector images, the file size increases only with the addition of more vectors.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] There are two types of image file compression algorithms: lossless and lossy.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Lossless compression algorithms reduce file size while preserving a perfect copy of the original uncompressed image.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Lossless compression generally, but not always, results in larger files than lossy compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Lossless compression should be used to avoid accumulating stages of re-compression when editing images.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Lossy compression algorithms preserve a representation of the original uncompressed image that may appear to be a perfect copy, but is not a perfect copy.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Often lossy compression is able to achieve smaller file sizes than lossless compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Most lossy compression algorithms allow for variable compression that trades image quality for file size.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Including proprietary types, there are hundreds of image file types.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The PNG, JPEG, and GIF formats are most often used to display images on the Internet.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Some of these graphic formats are listed and briefly described below, separated into the two main families of graphics: raster and vector.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Raster images are further divided into formats primarily aimed at (web) delivery (i.e., supporting relatively strong compression) versus formats primarily aimed at authoring or interchange (uncompressed or only relatively weak compression).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] In addition to straight image formats, Metafile formats are portable formats that can include both raster and vector information.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Examples are application-independent formats such as WMF and EMF.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The metafile format is an intermediate format.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Most applications open metafiles and then save them in their own native format.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Page description language refers to formats used to describe the layout of a printed page containing text, objects, and images.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group) is a lossy compression method; JPEG-compressed images are usually stored in the JFIF (JPEG File Interchange Format) or the Exif (Exchangeable Image File Format) file format.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The JPEG filename extension is JPG or JPEG.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Nearly every digital camera can save images in the JPEG format, which supports eight-bit grayscale images and 24-bit color images (eight bits each for red, green, and blue).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] JPEG applies lossy compression to images, which can result in a significant reduction of the file size.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Applications can determine the degree of compression to apply, and the amount of compression affects the visual quality of the result.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] When not too great, the compression does not noticeably affect or detract from the image's quality, but JPEG files suffer generational degradation when repeatedly edited and saved.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The GIF (Graphics Interchange Format) is in normal use limited to an 8-bit palette, or 256 colors (while 24-bit color depth is technically possible).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] GIF is most suitable for storing graphics with few colors, such as simple diagrams, shapes, logos, and cartoon-style images, as it uses LZW lossless compression, which is more effective when large areas have a single color and less effective for photographic or dithered images.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Due to GIF's simplicity and age, it achieved almost universal software support.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Due to its animation capabilities, it is still widely used to provide image animation effects, despite its low compression ratio compared to modern video formats.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The PNG (Portable Network Graphics) file format was created as a free, open-source alternative to GIF.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The PNG file format supports 8-bit (256 colors) paletted images (with optional transparency for all palette colors) and 24-bit truecolor (16 million colors) or 48-bit truecolor with and without an alpha channel – while GIF supports only 8-bit palettes with a single transparent color.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Compared to JPEG, PNG excels when the image has large, uniformly colored areas.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Even for photographs – where JPEG is often the choice for final distribution since its lossy compression typically yields smaller file sizes – PNG is still well-suited to storing images during the editing process because of its lossless compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] PNG provides a patent-free replacement for GIF (though GIF is itself now patent-free) and can also replace many common uses of TIFF.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Indexed-color, grayscale, and truecolor images are supported, plus an optional alpha channel.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The Adam7 interlacing allows an early preview, even when only a small percentage of the image data has been transmitted—useful in online viewing applications like web browsers.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] PNG can store gamma and chromaticity data, as well as ICC profiles, for accurate color matching on heterogeneous platforms.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Animated formats derived from PNG are MNG and APNG, which is backwards compatible with PNG and supported by most browsers.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 is a compression standard enabling both lossless and lossy storage.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The compression methods used are different from the ones in standard JFIF/JPEG; they improve quality and compression ratios, but also require more computational power to process.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 also adds features that are missing in JPEG.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It is not nearly as common as JPEG but it is used currently in professional movie editing and distribution (some digital cinemas, for example, use JPEG 2000 for individual movie frames).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] WebP is an open image format released in 2010 that uses both lossless and lossy compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It was designed by Google to reduce image file size to speed up web page loading: its principal purpose is to supersede JPEG as the primary format for photographs on the web.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding and uses a container based on RIFF.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] In 2011, Google added an "Extended File Format" allowing WebP support for animation, ICC profile, XMP and Exif metadata, and tiling.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The support for animation allowed for converting older animated GIFs to animated WebP.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The WebP container (i.e., RIFF container for WebP) allows feature support over and above the basic use case of WebP (i.e., a file containing a single image encoded as a VP8 key frame).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Most typical raster formats cannot store HDR data (32 bit floating point values per pixel component), which is why some relatively old or complex formats are still predominant here, and worth mentioning separately.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Newer alternatives are showing up, though.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] RGBE is the format for HDR images originating from Radiance and also supported by Adobe Photoshop.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] JPEG-HDR is a file format from Dolby Labs similar to RGBE encoding, standardized as JPEG XT Part 2.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] JPEG XT Part 7 includes support for encoding floating point HDR images in the base 8-bit JPEG file using enhancement layers encoded with four profiles (A-D); Profile A is based on the RGBE format and Profile B on the XDepth format from Trellis Management.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF) is an image container format that was standardized by MPEG on the basis of the ISO base media file format.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] While HEIF can be used with any image compression format, the HEIF standard specifies the storage of HEVC intra-coded images and HEVC-coded image sequences taking advantage of inter-picture prediction.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] AVIF is an image container, that is used to store AV1 encoded images.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It was created by Alliance for open media (AOMedia) and is completely open source and royalty-free.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It supports encoding images in 8, 10 and 12-bit depth.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] JPEG XL is a royalty-free raster-graphics file format that supports both lossy and lossless compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It supports reversible recompression of existing JPEG files, as well as high-precision HDR (up to 32-bit floating point values per pixel component).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It is designed to be usable for both delivery and authoring use cases.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The TIFF (Tag Image File Format) format is a flexible format usually using either the TIFF or TIF filename extension.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The tag structure was designed to be easily extendible, and many vendors have introduced proprietary special-purpose tags – with the result that no one reader handles every flavor of TIFF file.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] TIFFs can be lossy or lossless, depending on the technique chosen for storing the pixel data.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Some offer relatively good lossless compression for bi-level (black&white) images.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Some digital cameras can save images in TIFF format, using the LZW compression algorithm for lossless storage.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] TIFF image format is not widely supported by web browsers, but it remains widely accepted as a photograph file standard in the printing business.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] TIFF can handle device-specific color spaces, such as the CMYK defined by a particular set of printing press inks.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] OCR (Optical Character Recognition) software packages commonly generate some form of TIFF image (often monochromatic) for scanned text pages.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The BMP file format (Windows bitmap) is a raster-based, device-independent file type designed in the early days of computer graphics.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It handles graphic files within the Microsoft Windows OS.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Typically, BMP files are uncompressed and therefore large and lossless; their advantage is their simple structure and wide acceptance in Windows programs.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Netpbm format is a family including the portable pixmap file format (PPM), the portable graymap file format (PGM), and the portable bitmap file format (PBM).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] These are either pure ASCII files or raw binary files with an ASCII header that provide very basic functionality and serve as a lowest common denominator for converting pixmap, graymap, or bitmap files between different platforms.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Several applications refer to them collectively as PNM (Portable Any Map).
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] As opposed to the raster image formats above (where the data describes the characteristics of each individual pixel), vector image formats contain a geometric description which can be rendered smoothly at any desired display size.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] At some point, all vector graphics must be rasterized in order to be displayed on digital monitors.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Vector images may also be displayed with analog CRT technology such as that used in some electronic test equipment, medical monitors, radar displays, laser shows and early video games.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Plotters are printers that use vector data rather than pixel data to draw graphics.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile) is a file format for 2D vector graphics, raster graphics, and text, and is defined by ISO/IEC 8632.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] All graphical elements can be specified in a textual source file that can be compiled into a binary file or one of two text representations.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] CGM provides a means of graphics data interchange for computer representation of 2D graphical information independent from any particular application, system, platform, or device.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It has been adopted to some extent in the areas of technical illustration and professional design, but has largely been superseded by formats such as SVG and DXF.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The Gerber format (aka Extended Gerber, RS-274X) is a 2D bi-level image description format developed by Ucamco.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] It is the de facto standard format for printed circuit board or PCB software.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) is an open standard created and developed by the World Wide Web Consortium to address the need (and attempts of several corporations) for a versatile, scriptable and all-purpose vector format for the web and otherwise.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] The SVG format does not have a compression scheme of its own, but due to the textual nature of XML, an SVG graphic can be compressed using a program such as gzip.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] Because of its scripting potential, SVG is a key component in web applications: interactive web pages that look and act like applications.
[src:pillow-imaging/image-file-format] These are formats containing both pixel and vector data, possible other data, e.g. the interactive features of PDF.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG supports palette-based images (with palettes of 24-bit RGB or 32-bit RGBA colors), grayscale images (with or without an alpha channel for transparency), and full-color non-palette-based RGB or RGBA images.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The PNG working group designed the format for transferring images on the Internet, not for professional-quality print graphics; therefore, non-RGB color spaces such as CMYK are not supported.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] A PNG file contains a single image in an extensible structure of *chunks*, encoding the basic pixels and other information such as textual comments and integrity checks documented in RFC 2083.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG files have the ".png" file extension and the "image/png" MIME media type.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG was published as an informational RFC 2083 in March 1997 and as the standard ISO/IEC 15948:2004 in 2004.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The motivation for creating the PNG format was the announcement on 28 December 1994 that implementations of the Graphics Interchange Format (GIF) format would have to pay royalties to Unisys due to their patent of the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) data compression algorithm used in GIF.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This led to a flurry of criticism from Usenet users.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] One of them was Thomas Boutell, who on 4 January 1995 posted a precursory discussion thread on the Usenet newsgroup "comp.graphics" in which he devised a plan for a free alternative to GIF.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Other users in that thread put forth many propositions that would later be part of the final file format.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Oliver Fromme, author of the popular JPEG viewer QPEG, proposed the PING name, eventually becoming PNG, a recursive acronym meaning *PING is not GIF*, and also the .png extension.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Other suggestions later implemented included the deflate compression algorithm and 24-bit color support, the lack of the latter in GIF also motivating the team to create their file format.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The group would become known as the PNG Development Group, and as the discussion rapidly expanded, it later used a mailing list associated with a CompuServe forum.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The full specification of PNG was released under the approval of World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) on 1 October 1996, and later as RFC 2083 on 15 January 1997.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The specification was revised on 31 December 1998 as version 1.1, which addressed technical problems for gamma and color correction.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Version 1.2, released on 11 August 1999, added the iTXt chunk as the specification's only change, and a reformatted version of 1.2 was released as a second edition of the W3C standard on 10 November 2003, and as an International Standard (ISO/IEC 15948:2004) on 3 March 2004.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Although GIF allows for animation, it was initially decided that PNG should be a single-image format.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In 2001, the developers of PNG published the Multiple-image Network Graphics (MNG) format, with support for animation.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] MNG achieved moderate application support, but not enough among mainstream web browsers and no usage among web site designers or publishers.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In 2008, certain Mozilla developers published the Animated Portable Network Graphics (APNG) format with similar goals.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] APNG is a format that is natively supported by Gecko- and Presto-based web browsers and is also commonly used for thumbnails on Sony's PlayStation Portable system (using the normal PNG file extension).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In 2017, Chromium based browsers adopted APNG support.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In January 2020, Microsoft Edge became Chromium based, thus inheriting support for APNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] With this all major browsers now support APNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The PNG Working Group has been chartered by the W3C, since September 14, 2021, to maintain and develop for the PNG specification.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The third edition of PNG specification, which adds the proper support of APNG, high dynamic range (HDR) and Exif data, was published as the first public working draft on October 25, 2022, and ultimately as a W3C Recommendation on June 24, 2025.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The original PNG specification was authored by an ad hoc group of computer graphics experts and enthusiasts.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Discussions and decisions about the format were conducted by email.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] After the header, comes a series of chunks, each of which conveys certain information about the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Chunks declare themselves as *critical* or *ancillary*, and a program encountering an ancillary chunk that it does not understand can safely ignore it.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] A chunk consists of four parts: length (4 bytes, big-endian), chunk type/name (4 bytes), chunk data (length bytes) and CRC (cyclic redundancy code/checksum; 4 bytes).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The CRC is a network-byte-order CRC-32 computed over the chunk type and chunk data, but not the length.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Chunk types are given a four-letter case sensitive ASCII type/name; compare FourCC.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The case of the different letters in the name (bit 5 of the numeric value of the character) is a bit field that provides the decoder with some information on the nature of chunks it does not recognize.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The case of the first letter indicates whether the chunk is critical or not.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] If the first letter is uppercase, the chunk is critical; if not, the chunk is ancillary.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Critical chunks contain information that is necessary to read the file.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] If a decoder encounters a critical chunk it does not recognize, it must abort reading the file or supply the user with an appropriate warning.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The case of the second letter indicates whether the chunk is "public" (either in the specification or the registry of special-purpose public chunks) or "private" (not standardized).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Uppercase is public and lowercase is private.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This ensures that public and private chunk names can never conflict with each other (although two private chunk names could conflict).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The third letter must be uppercase to conform to the PNG specification.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Decoders should treat a chunk with a lower-case third letter the same as any other unrecognized chunk.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The case of the fourth letter indicates whether the chunk is safe to copy by editors that do not recognize it.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] If lowercase, the chunk may be safely copied regardless of the extent of modifications to the file.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] If uppercase, it may only be copied if the modifications have not touched any critical chunks.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] A decoder must be able to interpret critical chunks to read and render a PNG file.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Other image attributes that can be stored in PNG files include gamma values, background color, and textual metadata information.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG also supports color management through the inclusion of ICC color profiles.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Pixels in PNG images are numbers that may be either indices of sample data in the palette or the sample data itself.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The palette is a separate table contained in the PLTE chunk.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Sample data for a single pixel consists of a tuple of between one and four numbers.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Whether the pixel data represents palette indices or explicit sample values, the numbers are referred to as channels and every number in the image is encoded with an identical format.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The permitted formats encode each number as an unsigned integer value using a fixed number of bits, referred to in the PNG specification as the *bit depth*.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Notice that this is not the same as color depth, which is commonly used to refer to the total number of bits in each pixel, not each channel.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The permitted bit depths are summarized in the table along with the total number of bits used for each pixel.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The number of channels depends on whether the image is grayscale or color and whether it has an alpha channel.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG allows the following combinations of channels, called the *color type*.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The color type is specified as an 8-bit value however only the low three bits are used and, even then, only the five combinations listed above are permitted.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] With indexed color images, the palette always stores trichromatic colors at a depth of 8 bits per channel (24 bits per palette entry).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Additionally, an optional list of 8-bit alpha values for the palette entries may be included; if not included, or if shorter than the palette, the remaining palette entries are assumed to be opaque.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The palette must not have more entries than the image bit depth allows for, but it may have fewer (for example, if an image with 8-bit pixels only uses 90 colors then it does not need palette entries for all 256 colors).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The palette must contain entries for all the pixel values present in the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The standard allows indexed color PNGs to have 1, 2, 4 or 8 bits per pixel; grayscale images with no alpha channel may have 1, 2, 4, 8 or 16 bits per pixel.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Everything else uses a bit depth per channel of either 8 or 16.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The combinations this allows are given in the table above.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The standard requires that decoders can read all supported color formats, but many image editors can only produce a small subset of them.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG offers a variety of transparency options.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] With true-color and grayscale images either a single pixel value can be declared as transparent or an alpha channel can be added (enabling any percentage of partial transparency to be used).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] For paletted images, alpha values can be added to palette entries.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The number of such values stored may be less than the total number of palette entries, in which case the remaining entries are considered fully opaque.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The scanning of pixel values for binary transparency is supposed to be performed before any color reduction to avoid pixels becoming unintentionally transparent.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This is most likely to pose an issue for systems that can decode 16-bits-per-channel images (as is required for compliance with the specification) but only output at 8 bits per channel (the norm for all but the highest end systems).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Alpha *storage* can be "associated" ("premultiplied") or "unassociated", but PNG standardized on "unassociated" ("non-premultiplied") alpha, which means that imagery is not alpha *encoded*; the emissions represented in RGB are not the emissions at the pixel level.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This means that the over operation will multiply the RGB emissions by the alpha, and cannot represent emission and occlusion properly.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG uses DEFLATE, a non-patented lossless data compression algorithm involving a combination of LZ77 and Huffman coding.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Permissively licensed DEFLATE implementations, such as zlib, are widely available.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Compared to formats with lossy compression, such as JPEG, choosing higher compression settings can slow processing without significantly reducing file size.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Before DEFLATE is applied, the data is transformed via a prediction method: a single *filter method* is used for the entire image, while for each image line, a *filter type* is chosen to transform the data to make it more efficiently compressible.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The filter type used for a scanline is prepended to the scanline to enable inline decompression.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] There is only one filter method in the current PNG specification (denoted method 0), and thus in practice the only choice is which filter type to apply to each line.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] For this method, the filter predicts the value of each pixel based on the values of previous neighboring pixels, and subtracts the predicted color of the pixel from the actual value, as in DPCM.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] An image line filtered in this way is often more compressible than the raw image line would be, especially if it is similar to the line above, since the differences from prediction will generally be clustered around 0, rather than spread over all possible image values.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This is particularly important in relating separate rows, since DEFLATE has no understanding that an image is a 2D entity, and instead just sees the image data as a stream of bytes.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Filters are applied to byte values, not pixels; pixel values may be one or two bytes, or several values per byte, but never cross byte boundaries.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The Paeth filter is based on an algorithm by Alan W.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Compare to the version of DPCM used in lossless JPEG, and to the discrete wavelet transform using 1 × 2, 2 × 1, or (for the Paeth predictor) 2 × 2 windows and Haar wavelets.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Compression is further improved by choosing filter types adaptively on a line-by-line basis.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This improvement, and a heuristic method of implementing it commonly used by PNG-writing software, were created by Lee Daniel Crocker, who tested the methods on many images during the creation of the format; the choice of filter is a component of file size optimization, as discussed below.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] If interlacing is used, each stage of the interlacing is filtered separately, meaning that the image can be progressively rendered as each stage is received; however, interlacing generally makes compression less effective.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG offers an optional 2-dimensional, 7-pass interlacing scheme—the Adam7 algorithm.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This is more sophisticated than GIF's 1-dimensional, 4-pass scheme, and allows a clearer low-resolution image to be visible earlier in the transfer, particularly if interpolation algorithms such as bicubic interpolation are used.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] However, the 7-pass scheme tends to reduce the data's compressibility more than simpler schemes.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The core PNG format does not support animation.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] MNG is an extension to PNG that does; it was designed by members of the PNG Group.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] MNG shares PNG's basic structure and chunks, but it is significantly more complex and has a different file signature, which automatically renders it incompatible with standard PNG decoders.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This means that most web browsers and applications either never supported MNG or dropped support for it.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The complexity of MNG led to the proposal of APNG by developers at the Mozilla Foundation.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] It is based on PNG, supports animation and is simpler than MNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] APNG offers fallback to single-image display for PNG decoders that do not support APNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Today, the APNG format is supported by all major web browsers.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] APNG is supported in Firefox 3.0 and up, Pale Moon (all versions), and Safari 8.0 and up.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Chromium 59.0 added APNG support, followed by Google Chrome.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Opera supported APNG in versions 10–12.1, but support lapsed in version 15 when it switched to the Blink rendering engine; support was re-added in Opera 46 (inherited from Chromium 59).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Microsoft Edge has supported APNG since version 79.0, when it switched to a Chromium-based engine.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The PNG Group decided in April 2007 not to embrace APNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Several alternatives were under discussion, including ANG, aNIM/mPNG, "PNG in GIF" and its subset "RGBA in GIF".
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] However, currently only APNG has widespread support.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] With the release of the third edition of the PNG specification in June 2025, now maintained by the PNG working group, APNG is finally incorporated into the specification as an extension.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Displayed in the fashion of hex editors, with on the left side byte values shown in hex format, and on the right side their equivalent characters from ISO-8859-1 with unrecognized and control characters replaced with periods.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Offsets 8 and 9 of the IDAT Chunk represent the required 2-byte header of the zlib data format.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Offset 16 (of the same chunk) represents the 4-byte footer required by the same format.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Additionally the PNG signature and individual chunks are marked with colors.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Note they are easy to identify because of their human readable type names (in this example PNG, IHDR, IDAT, and IEND).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG images are less widely supported by older browsers.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In particular, IE6 has limited support for PNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Using PNG instead of a high-quality JPEG for such images would result in a large increase in file size with negligible gain in quality.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In comparison, when storing images that contain text, line art, or graphics – images with sharp transitions and large areas of solid color – the PNG format can compress image data more than JPEG can.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Additionally, PNG is lossless, while JPEG produces visual artifacts around high-contrast areas.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] (Such artifacts depend on the settings used in the JPG compression; they can be quite noticeable when a low-quality [high-compression] setting is used.) Where an image contains both sharp transitions and photographic parts, a choice must be made between the two effects.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] JPEG's lossy compression also suffers from generation loss, where repeatedly decoding and re-encoding an image to save it again causes a loss of information each time, degrading the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Because PNG is lossless, it is suitable for storing images to be edited.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] While PNG is reasonably efficient when compressing photographic images, there are lossless compression formats designed specifically for photographic images, lossless WebP and Adobe DNG (digital negative) for example.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] However these formats are either not widely supported, or are proprietary.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] An image can be stored losslessly and converted to JPEG format only for distribution, so that there is no generation loss.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] While the PNG specification does not explicitly include a standard for embedding Exif image data from sources such as digital cameras, the preferred method for embedding EXIF data in a PNG is to use the non-critical ancillary chunk label `eXIf`.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Early web browsers did not support PNG images; JPEG and GIF were the main image formats.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] JPEG was commonly used when exporting images containing gradients for web pages, because of GIF's limited color depth.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] However, JPEG compression causes a gradient to blur slightly.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] A PNG format reproduces a gradient as accurately as possible for a given bit depth, while keeping the file size small.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG became the optimal choice for small gradient images as web browser support for the format improved.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] No images at all are needed to display gradients in modern browsers, as gradients can be created using CSS.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] JPEG-LS is an image format by the Joint Photographic Experts Group, though far less widely known and supported than the other lossy JPEG format discussed above.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] It is directly comparable with PNG, and has a standard set of test images.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] On the Waterloo Repertoire ColorSet, a standard set of test images (unrelated to the JPEG-LS conformance test set), JPEG-LS generally performs better than PNG, by 10–15%, but on some images PNG performs substantially better, on the order of 50–75%.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Thus, if both of these formats are options and file size is an important criterion, they should both be considered, depending on the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] JPEG XL is another, much improved, lossless or lossy format, that is supported much less, developed to replace lossless formats like PNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] JPEG XL is more than 50% smaller than JPEG, and that can happen while it's lossless, therefore making it even smaller than PNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] It also supports high dynamic range, wide colour gamuts, and large colour depths.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] JPEG XL is also very efficient at decoding, and provides smooth transitions from the formats it intends to replace, losslessly able to convert from JPEG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] It also excels at compressing without compromising on fidelity.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Tag Image File Format (TIFF) is a format that incorporates an extremely wide range of options.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] While this makes TIFF useful as a generic format for interchange between professional image editing applications, it makes adding support for it to applications a much bigger task and so it has little support in applications not concerned with image manipulation (such as web browsers).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The high level of extensibility also means that most applications provide only a subset of possible features, potentially creating user confusion and compatibility issues.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The most common general-purpose, lossless compression algorithm used with TIFF is Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This compression technique, also used in GIF, was covered by patents until 2003.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] TIFF also supports the compression algorithm PNG uses (i.e.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Compression Tag 000816 'Adobe-style') with medium usage and support by applications.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] TIFF also offers special-purpose lossless compression algorithms like CCITT Group IV, which can compress bilevel images (e.g., faxes or black-and-white text) better than PNG's compression algorithm.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG supports non-premultiplied alpha only whereas TIFF also supports "associated" (premultiplied) alpha.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] WebP is a format invented by Google that was intended to replace PNG, JPEG, and GIF.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] WebP files allow for both lossy and lossless compression, while PNG only allows for lossless compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] WebP also supports animation, something that only GIF files could previously accomplish.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The main improvements of WebP over PNG, however, are the large reduction in file size and therefore faster loading times when embedded into websites.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Google claims that lossless WebP images are 26% smaller than PNG files.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] WebP has received criticism for being incompatible with various image editing programs and social media websites, unlike PNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] WebP is also not supported across all web browsers, which may require web image hosters to create a fallback image to display to the user, negating the potential storage savings of WebP.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] AVIF is an image format developed by the Alliance for Open Media.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] AVIF was designed by the foundation to make up for the shortcomings of other image codecs, including PNG, GIF, and WebP.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] AVIF is generally smaller in size than both WebP and PNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] AVIF supports animation while PNG previously did not.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] However, like WebP, AVIF is supported across fewer applications than PNG.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The official reference implementation of the PNG format is the programming library *libpng*.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] It is published as free software under the terms of a permissive free software license.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Therefore, it is usually found as an important system library in free operating systems.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Some programs bundled with popular operating systems which support PNG include Microsoft's Paint and Apple's Photos/iPhoto and Preview, with the GIMP also often being bundled with popular Linux distributions.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Adobe Fireworks (formerly by Macromedia) uses PNG as its native file format, allowing other image editors and preview utilities to view the flattened image.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] However, Fireworks by default also stores metadata for layers, animation, vector data, text and effects.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Such files should not be distributed directly.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Fireworks can instead export the image as an optimized PNG without the extra metadata for use on web pages, etc.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG support first appeared in 1997, in Internet Explorer 4.0b1 (32-bit only for NT), and in Netscape 4.04.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Despite calls by the Free Software Foundation and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), tools such as gif2png, and campaigns such as Burn All GIFs, PNG adoption on websites was fairly slow due to late and buggy support in Internet Explorer, particularly regarding transparency.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG is the most used image file format on the web since 2018.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG compatible browsers include: Apple Safari, Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Opera, Camino, Internet Explorer, Microsoft Edge and many others.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] For the complete comparison, see Comparison of web browsers (Image format support).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Especially versions of Internet Explorer (Windows) below 9.0 (released 2011) had numerous problems which prevented it from correctly rendering PNG images.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG icons have been supported in most distributions of Linux since at least 1999, in desktop environments such as GNOME.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In 2006, Microsoft Windows support for PNG icons was introduced in Windows Vista.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG icons are supported in AmigaOS 4, AROS, macOS, iOS and MorphOS as well.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] In addition, Android makes extensive use of PNGs.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Compared to GIF files, a PNG file with the same information (256 colors, no ancillary chunks/metadata), compressed by an effective compressor is normally smaller than a GIF image.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Depending on the file and the compressor, PNG may range from somewhat smaller (10%) to significantly smaller (50%) to somewhat larger (5%), but is rarely significantly larger for large images.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] However, some versions of Adobe Photoshop, CorelDRAW and MS Paint provide poor PNG compression, creating the impression that GIF is more efficient.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Color depth can range from 1 to 64 bits per pixel.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] PNG supports metadata—this may be useful for editing, but unnecessary for viewing, as on websites.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] As each pass of the Adam7 algorithm is separately filtered, this can increase file size.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] As a precompression stage, each line is filtered by a predictive filter, which can change from line to line.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] As the ultimate DEFLATE step operates on the whole image's filtered data, one cannot optimize this row-by-row; the choice of filter for each row is thus potentially very variable, though heuristics exist.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] With additional computation, DEFLATE compressors can produce smaller files.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Interlacing is a trade-off: it dramatically speeds up early rendering of large files (improves latency), but may increase file size (decrease throughput) for little gain, particularly for small files.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Although PNG is a lossless format, PNG encoders can preprocess image data in a lossy fashion to improve PNG compression.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] For example, quantizing a truecolor PNG to 256 colors allows the indexed color type to be used for a likely reduction in file size.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Some programs are more efficient than others when saving PNG files, this relates to implementation of the PNG compression used by the program.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Many graphics programs (such as Apple's Preview software) save PNGs with large amounts of metadata and color-correction data that are generally unnecessary for Web viewing.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Unoptimized PNG files from Adobe Fireworks are also notorious for this since they contain options to make the image editable in supported editors.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Also CorelDRAW (at least version 11) sometimes produces PNGs which cannot be opened by Internet Explorer (versions 6–8).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Adobe Photoshop's performance on PNG files has improved in the CS Suite when using the Save For Web feature (which also allows explicit PNG/8 use).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Adobe's Fireworks saves larger PNG files than many programs by default.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This stems from the mechanics of its *Save* format: the images produced by Fireworks' save function include large, private chunks, containing complete layer and vector information.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] When saved with the *Export* option, Fireworks' PNGs are competitive with those produced by other image editors, but are no longer editable as anything but flattened bitmaps.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Fireworks is unable to save size-optimized vector-editable PNGs.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Poor compression increases the PNG file size but does not affect the image quality or compatibility of the file with other programs.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] When the color depth of a truecolor image is reduced to an 8-bit palette (as in GIF), the resulting image data is typically much smaller.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Thus a truecolor PNG is typically larger than a color-reduced GIF, although PNG could store the color-reduced version as a palettized file of comparable size.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Conversely, some tools, when saving images as PNGs, automatically save them as truecolor, even if the original data use only 8-bit color, thus bloating the file unnecessarily.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Both factors can lead to the misconception that PNG files are larger than equivalent GIF files.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] A simple comparison of their features is listed below.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Before `zopflipng` was available, a good way in practice to perform a png optimization is to use a combination of 2 tools in sequence for optimal compression: one which optimizes filters (and removes ancillary chunks), and one which optimizes DEFLATE.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Although pngout offers both, only one type of filter can be specified in a single run, therefore it can be used with a wrapper tool or in combination with pngcrush, acting as a re-deflater, like `advdef`.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] For removing ancillary chunks, most PNG optimization tools have the ability to remove all color correction data from PNG files (gamma, white balance, ICC color profile, standard RGB color profile).
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] This often results in much smaller file sizes.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] `pngcrush`, `pngout`, and `zopflipng` all offer options applying one of the filter types 0–4 globally (using the same filter type for all lines) or with a "pseudo filter" (numbered 5), which for each line chooses one of the filter types 0–4 using an adaptive algorithm.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] `zopflipng` offers 3 different adaptive method, including a brute-force search that attempts to optimize the filtering.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] `pngout` and `zopflipng` provide an option to preserve/reuse the line-by-line filter set present in the input image.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] `pngcrush` and `zopflipng` provide options to try different filter strategies in a single run and choose the best.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] The freeware command line version of `pngout` doesn't offer this, but the commercial version, `pngoutwin`, does.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Zopfli and the LZMA SDK provide DEFLATE implementations that can produce higher compression ratios than the zlib reference implementation at the cost of performance.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] AdvanceCOMP's `advpng` and `advdef` can use either of these libraries to re-compress PNG files.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Additionally, PNGOUT contains its own proprietary DEFLATE implementation.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] `advpng` doesn't have an option to apply filters and always uses filter 0 globally (leaving the image data unfiltered); therefore it should not be used where the image benefits significantly from filtering.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] By contrast, `advdef` from the same package doesn't deal with PNG structure and acts only as a re-deflater, retaining any existing filter settings.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Since icons intended for Windows Vista and later versions may contain PNG subimages, the optimizations can be applied to them as well.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] At least one icon editor, Pixelformer, is able to perform a special optimization pass while saving ICO files, thereby reducing their sizes.
[src:pillow-imaging/portable-network-graphics] Icons for macOS may also contain PNG subimages, yet there isn't such tool available.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] In computer graphics and digital photography, a **raster graphic**, **raster image**, or simply **raster** is a digital image made up of a rectangular grid of tiny colored (usually square) so-called pixels.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Unlike vector graphics which use mathematical formulas to describe shapes and lines, raster images store the exact color of each pixel, making them ideal for photographs and images with complex colors and details.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Raster images are characterized by their dimensions (width and height in pixels) and color depth (the number of bits per pixel).
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] They can be displayed on computer displays, printed on paper, or viewed on other media, and are stored in various image file formats.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The printing and prepress industries know raster graphics as **contones** (from "continuous tones").
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] In contrast, *line art* is usually implemented as vector graphics in digital systems.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Many raster manipulations map directly onto the mathematical formalisms of linear algebra, where mathematical objects of matrix structure are of central concern.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Raster or **gridded data** may be the result of a gridding procedure.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The word "raster" has its origins in the Latin *rastrum* (a rake), which is derived from *radere* (to scrape).
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] It originates from the raster scan of cathode-ray tube (CRT) video monitors, which draw the image line by line by magnetically or electrostatically steering a focused electron beam.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] By association, it can also refer to a rectangular grid of pixels.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The modern word rastrum refers to a device for drawing musical staff lines.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The fundamental strategy underlying the raster data model is the tessellation of a plane, into a two-dimensional array of squares, each called a *cell* or *pixel* (from "picture element").
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] In digital photography, the plane is the visual field as projected onto the image sensor; in computer art, the plane is a virtual canvas; in geographic information systems, the plane is a projection of the Earth's surface.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The size of each square pixel, known as the *resolution* or *support*, is constant across the grid.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] A single numeric value is then stored for each pixel.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] For most images, this value is a visible color, but other measurements are possible, even numeric codes for qualitative categories.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Each raster grid has a specified *pixel format*, the data type for each number.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Common pixel formats are binary, grayscale, palettized, and full-color, where color depth determines the fidelity of the colors represented, and color space determines the range of color coverage (which is often less than the full range of human color vision).
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Most modern color raster formats represent color using 24 bits (over 16 million distinct colors), with 8 bits (values 0–255) for each color channel (red, green, and blue).
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The digital sensors used for remote sensing and astronomy are often able to detect and store wavelengths beyond the visible spectrum; the large CCD bitmapped sensor at the Vera C.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Rubin Observatory captures 3.2 gigapixels in a single image (6.4 GB raw), over six color channels which exceed the spectral range of human color vision.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Most computer images are stored in raster graphics formats or compressed variations, including GIF, JPEG, and PNG, which are popular on the World Wide Web.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] A **raster data** structure is based on a (usually rectangular, square-based) tessellation of the 2D plane into cells, each containing a single value.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] To store the data in a file, the two-dimensional array must be serialized.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The most common way to do this is a *row-major* format, in which the cells along the first (usually top) row are listed left to right, followed immediately by those of the second row, and so on.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] In the example at right, the cells of tessellation A are overlaid on the point pattern B resulting in an array C of quadrant counts representing the number of points in each cell.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] For purposes of visualization a lookup table has been used to color each of the cells in an image D.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] To reconstruct the two-dimensional grid, the file must include a *header* section at the beginning that contains at least the number of columns, and the pixel datatype (especially the number of bits or bytes per value) so the reader knows where each value ends to start reading the next one.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Headers may also include the number of rows, georeferencing parameters for geographic data, or other metadata tags, such as those specified in the Exif standard.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] High-resolution raster grids contain a large number of pixels, and thus consume a large amount of storage.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] This has led to multiple approaches to compressing the data volume into smaller files.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The most common strategy is to look for patterns or trends in the pixel values, then store a parameterized form of the pattern instead of the original data.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Common raster compression algorithms include run-length encoding (RLE), JPEG, LZ (the basis for PNG and ZIP), Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) (the basis for GIF), and others.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] For example, Run length encoding looks for repeated values in the array, and replaces them with the value and the number of times it appears.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] This technique is very efficient when there are large areas of identical values, such as a line drawing, but in a photograph where pixels are usually slightly different from their neighbors, the RLE file would be up to twice the size of the original.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Some compression algorithms, such as RLE and LZW, are *lossless*, where the original pixel values can be perfectly regenerated from the compressed data.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Other algorithms, such as JPEG, are *lossy*, because the parameterized patterns are only an approximation of the original pixel values, so the latter can only be estimated from the compressed data.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Vector images (line work) can be rasterized (converted into pixels), and raster images vectorized (raster images converted into vector graphics), by software.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] In both cases, some information is lost, although certain vectorization operations can recreate salient information, as in the case of optical character recognition.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Early mechanical televisions developed in the 1920s employed rasterization principles.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Electronic television based on cathode-ray tube displays are raster scanned with horizontal rasters painted left to right, and the raster lines painted top to bottom.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Modern flat-panel displays such as LED monitors still use a raster approach.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Each on-screen pixel directly corresponds to a small number of bits in memory.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The screen is refreshed simply by scanning through pixels and coloring them according to each set of bits.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The refresh procedure, being speed critical, is often implemented by dedicated circuitry, often as a part of a graphics processing unit.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Using this approach, the computer contains an area of memory that holds all the data that are to be displayed.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The central processor writes data into this region of memory and the video controller collects them from there.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The bits of data stored in this block of memory are related to the eventual pattern of pixels that will be used to construct an image on the display.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] An early scanned display with raster computer graphics was invented in the late 1960s by A.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Michael Noll at Bell Labs, but its patent application filed February 5, 1970, was abandoned at the Supreme Court in 1977 over the issue of the patentability of computer software.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] During the 1970s and 1980s, pen plotters, using vector graphics, were common for creating precise drawings, especially on large format paper.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] However, since then almost all printers create the printed image as a raster grid, including both laser and inkjet printers.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] When the source information is vector, rendering specifications and software such as PostScript are used to create the raster image.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Three-dimensional voxel raster graphics are employed in video games and are also used in medical imaging such as MRI scanners.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Geographic phenomena are commonly represented in a raster format in GIS.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The raster grid is *georeferenced*, so that each pixel (commonly called a *cell* in GIS because the "picture" part of "pixel" is not relevant) represents a square region of geographic space.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] The value of each cell then represents some measurable (qualitative or quantitative) property of that region, typically conceptualized as a field.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Examples of fields commonly represented in rasters include: temperature, population density, soil moisture, land cover, surface elevation, etc.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Two sampling models are used to derive cell values from the field: in a *lattice*, the value is measured at the center point of each cell; in a *grid*, the value is a summary (usually a mean or mode) of the value over the entire cell.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Raster graphics are resolution dependent, meaning they cannot scale up to an arbitrary resolution without loss of apparent quality.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] This property contrasts with the capabilities of vector graphics, which easily scale up to the quality of the device rendering them.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Raster graphics deal more practically than vector graphics with photographs and photo-realistic images, while vector graphics often serve better for typesetting or for graphic design.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Typically, a resolution of 150 to 300 PPI works well for 4-color process (CMYK) printing.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] However, for printing technologies that perform color mixing through dithering (halftone) rather than through overprinting (virtually all home/office inkjet and laser printers), printer DPI and image PPI have a very different meaning, and this can be misleading.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Because, through the dithering process, the printer builds a single image pixel out of several printer dots to increase color depth, the printer's DPI setting must be set far higher than the desired PPI to ensure sufficient color depth without sacrificing image resolution.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Thus, for instance, printing an image at 250 PPI may actually require a printer setting of 1200 DPI.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] When an image is rendered in a raster-based image editor, the image is composed of millions of pixels.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] At its core, a raster image editor works by manipulating each individual pixel.
[src:pillow-imaging/raster-graphics] Most pixel-based image editors work using the RGB color model, but some also allow the use of other color models, such as the CMYK color model.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The most important class in the Python Imaging Library is the `Image` class, defined in the module with the same name.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] You can create instances of this class in several ways; either by loading images from files, processing other images, or creating images from scratch.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] If successful, this function returns an `Image` object.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The `format` attribute identifies the source of an image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] If the image was not read from a file, it is set to None.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The size attribute is a 2-tuple containing width and height (in pixels).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The `mode` attribute defines the number and names of the bands in the image, and also the pixel type and depth.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Common modes are “L” (luminance) for grayscale images, “RGB” for true color images, and “CMYK” for pre-press images.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] If the file cannot be opened, an `OSError` exception is raised.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Once you have an instance of the `Image` class, you can use the methods defined by this class to process and manipulate the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The standard version of `show()` is not very efficient, since it saves the image to a temporary file and calls a utility to display the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] If you don’t have an appropriate utility installed, it won’t even work.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] When it does work though, it is very handy for debugging and tests.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The following sections provide an overview of the different functions provided in this library.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The Python Imaging Library supports a wide variety of image file formats.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] To read files from disk, use the `open()` function in the `Image` module.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] You don’t have to know the file format to open a file.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The library automatically determines the format based on the contents of the file.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] To save a file, use the `save()` method of the `Image` class.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] When saving files, the name becomes important.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Unless you specify the format, the library uses the filename extension to discover which file storage format to use.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] A second argument can be supplied to the `save()` method which explicitly specifies a file format.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] It is important to note that the library doesn’t decode or load the raster data unless it really has to.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] When you open a file, the file header is read to determine the file format and extract things like mode, size, and other properties required to decode the file, but the rest of the file is not processed until later.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] This means that opening an image file is a fast operation, which is independent of the file size and compression type.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The `Image` class contains methods allowing you to manipulate regions within an image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] To extract a sub-rectangle from an image, use the `crop()` method.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The region is defined by a 4-tuple, where coordinates are (left, upper, right, lower).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The Python Imaging Library uses a coordinate system with (0, 0) in the upper left corner.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Also note that coordinates refer to positions between the pixels, so the region in the above example is exactly 64x64 pixels.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The region could now be processed in a certain manner and pasted back.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] When pasting regions back, the size of the region must match the given region exactly.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] In addition, the region cannot extend outside the image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] However, the modes of the original image and the region do not need to match.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] If they don’t, the region is automatically converted before being pasted (see the section on Color transforms below for details).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] For more advanced tricks, the paste method can also take a transparency mask as an optional argument.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] In this mask, the value 255 indicates that the pasted image is opaque in that position (that is, the pasted image should be used as is).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The value 0 means that the pasted image is completely transparent.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Values in-between indicate different levels of transparency.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] For example, pasting an RGBA image and also using it as the mask would paste the opaque portion of the image but not its transparent background.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The Python Imaging Library also allows you to work with the individual bands of an multi-band image, such as an RGB image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The split method creates a set of new images, each containing one band from the original multi-band image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The merge function takes a mode and a tuple of images, and combines them into a new image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Note that for a single-band image, `split()` returns the image itself.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] To work with individual color bands, you may want to convert the image to “RGB” first.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The `PIL.Image.Image` class contains methods to `resize()` and `rotate()` an image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The former takes a tuple giving the new size, the latter the angle in degrees counter-clockwise.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] To rotate the image in 90 degree steps, you can either use the `rotate()` method or the `transpose()` method.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The latter can also be used to flip an image around its horizontal or vertical axis.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] `transpose(ROTATE)` operations can also be performed identically with `rotate()` operations, provided the `expand` flag is true, to provide for the same changes to the image’s size.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] A more general form of image transformations can be carried out via the `transform()` method.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Instead of calculating the size of the new image when resizing, you can also choose to resize relative to a given size.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The Python Imaging Library allows you to convert images between different pixel representations using the `convert()` method.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The library supports transformations between each supported mode and the “L” and “RGB” modes.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] To convert between other modes, you may have to use an intermediate image (typically an “RGB” image).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The Python Imaging Library provides a number of methods and modules that can be used to enhance images.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The `ImageFilter` module contains a number of pre-defined enhancement filters that can be used with the `filter()` method.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The `point()` method can be used to translate the pixel values of an image (e.g. image contrast manipulation).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] In most cases, a function object expecting one argument can be passed to this method.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Using the above technique, you can quickly apply any simple expression to an image.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Python only evaluates the portion of a logical expression as is necessary to determine the outcome, and returns the last value examined as the result of the expression.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] So if the expression above is false (0), Python does not look at the second operand, and thus returns 0.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] For more advanced image enhancement, you can use the classes in the `ImageEnhance` module.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Once created from an image, an enhancement object can be used to quickly try out different settings.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] You can adjust contrast, brightness, color balance and sharpness in this way.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The Python Imaging Library contains some basic support for image sequences (also called animation formats).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Supported sequence formats include FLI/FLC, GIF, and a few experimental formats.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] TIFF files can also contain more than one frame.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] When you open a sequence file, PIL automatically loads the first frame in the sequence.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] As seen in this example, you’ll get an `EOFError` exception when the sequence ends.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] You can create animated GIFs with Pillow, e.g.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The Python Imaging Library includes functions to print images, text and graphics on PostScript printers.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] As described earlier, the `open()` function of the `Image` module is used to open an image file.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] In most cases, you simply pass it the filename as an argument.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] If everything goes well, the result is an `PIL.Image.Image` object.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Otherwise, an `OSError` exception is raised.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] You can use a file-like object instead of the filename.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The object must implement `file.read`, `file.seek` and `file.tell` methods, and be opened in binary mode.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Note that the library rewinds the file (using `seek(0)`) before reading the image header.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] In addition, seek will also be used when the image data is read (by the load method).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] If the image file is embedded in a larger file, such as a tar file, you can use the `ContainerIO` or `TarIO` modules to access it.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Operations can be applied to multiple image files.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] For example, all PNG images in the current directory can be saved as JPEGs at reduced quality.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Since images can also be opened from a `Path` from the `pathlib` module, the example could be modified to use `pathlib` instead of the `glob` module.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Some decoders allow you to manipulate the image while reading it from a file.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] This can often be used to speed up decoding when creating thumbnails (when speed is usually more important than quality) and printing to a monochrome laser printer (when only a grayscale version of the image is needed).
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] The `draft()` method manipulates an opened but not yet loaded image so it as closely as possible matches the given mode and size.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] This is done by reconfiguring the image decoder.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] This is only available for JPEG and MPO files.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] Note that the resulting image may not exactly match the requested mode and size.
[src:pillow-imaging/tutorial] To make sure that the image is not larger than the given size, use the thumbnail method instead.
